<article>
    <h1>An&#xAD;jali Ragu&#xAD;ra&#xAD;man rec&#xAD;om&#xAD;mends</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201016/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-16"><time>2020-10-16</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | HAPPENINGS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>It is hard to imag­ine that a sea­soned per­former like Me­lanie Chisolm (above), or Sporty Spice as she is bet­ter known, had to wres­tle with iden­tity and self-ac­cep­tance is­sues.</p>
    <p>“Shad­ows eat me up,” she sings on Here I Am, a track from her lat­est record.</p>
    <p>“But I’m no longer scared of the dark, I see the light,” she adds, prov­ing that 21 years since her solo de­but North­ern Star, mu­sic is still her guid­ing light.</p>
    <p>And eight solo al­bums later, the 46-year-old singer is brim­ming with con­fi­dence, declar­ing on open­ing track Who I Am: “When I look in the mir­ror, I fi­nally like what I see.”</p>
    <p>In re­cent years, Chisolm has also picked up dee­jay­ing – she showed off her skills at a For­mula One after-party in Sin­ga­pore last year – and the elec­tronic in­flu­ences are ap­par­ent in the new al­bum.</p>
    <p>The puls­ing beats of Blame It On Me and the flirty club banger In And Out Of Love keep her in step with cur­rent pop stars like Dua Lipa and Carly Rae Jepsen.</p>
    <p>But tracks like Good Enough and the in­tro­spec­tive Nowhere To Run re­mind fans the record is a mu­si­cal di­ary of self-re­flec­tion.</p>

